<li class="commentbody highlighted" id="comment-244867">
			<cite><a href='http://smittenkitchen.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>deb</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-244867" title="">February 20, 2009</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">124</div>

				<p>Christina &#8212; I&#8217;d disagree. I&#8217;d argue that the trick to <i>crispy</i> cookies is melted butter. Melted butter also makes better crisp toppings. But softened butter is able to be whipped and suspend ingredients in a lighter state and makes for cakier, more tender cookies. This is the reason cakes always have softened butter with the other ingredients slowly whipped in, too.  Soft cookies = softened butter. Crisp cookies = melted butter. But, they&#8217;re the ones who test this stuff out &#8212; if anyone wants to try this recipe both ways, I am sure others would love to hear the input.</p>
<p>Lauren &#8212; I use <a href="http://astore.amazon.com/smitten-20/detail/B0001598EI" rel="nofollow">a scoop</a>. I have a few different sizes, but probably use the one linked the most.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
